        "context": "Something's Got to Give is an unfinished 1962 American feature film, directed by George Cukor for Twentieth Century-Fox and starring Marilyn Monroe, Dean Martin and Cyd Charisse. A remake of \"My Favorite Wife\" (1940), a screwball comedy starring Cary Grant and Irene Dunne, it was Monroe's last work, but from the beginning its production was disrupted by her personal troubles, and after her death on August 5, 1962, the film was abandoned. Most of its completed footage remained unseen for many years.\n\nSomething's Got to Give is an unfinished 1962 American feature film, directed by George Cukor for Twentieth Century-Fox and starring Marilyn Monroe, Dean Martin and Cyd Charisse. A remake of \"My Favorite Wife\" (1940), a screwball comedy starring Cary Grant and Irene Dunne, it was Monroe's last work, but from the beginning its production was disrupted by her personal troubles, and after her death on August 5, 1962, the film was abandoned. Most of its completed footage remained unseen for many years.\n\nMarilyn Monroe (born Norma Jeane Mortenson; June 1, 1926 \u2013 August 5, 1962) was an American actress and model. Famous for playing comic \"dumb blonde\" characters, she became one of the most popular sex symbols of the 1950s and was emblematic of the era's attitudes towards sexuality. Although she was a top-billed actress for only a decade, her films grossed $200 million by the time of her unexpected death in 1962. More than half a century after her death, she continues to be considered a major popular culture icon.\n\nMarilyn Monroe (born Norma Jeane Mortenson; June 1, 1926 \u2013 August 5, 1962) was an American actress and model. Famous for playing comic \"dumb blonde\" characters, she became one of the most popular sex symbols of the 1950s and was emblematic of the era's attitudes towards sexuality. Although she was a top-billed actress for only a decade, her films grossed $200 million by the time of her unexpected death in 1962. More than half a century after her death, she continues to be considered a major popular culture icon.",
        "gold_answer": "August 5, 1962",
        "level": "easy",
        "type": "bridge",
        "generated_trace": {
            "thought": "Thought: The question asks for the date Marilyn Monroe died, which happened before she finished her film \"Something's Got to Give\". The context provides this information. Specifically, the first paragraph about \"Something's Got to Give\" states, \"...after her death on August 5, 1962, the film was abandoned.\" The biographical paragraphs about Marilyn Monroe also state, \"Marilyn Monroe (born Norma Jeane Mortenson; June 1, 1926 \u2013 August 5, 1962)...\" Both sources confirm the date.\n",
